Interesting findings. Re: mental health, our society needs to severely destigmatise mental health. Mental illness is also a silent killer and some would say the ‚Äònew‚Äô silent killer.

This is a must read for everyone, regardless of your insurance provider.  I am glad Anthem is trying to address our health issues.  I have seen many changes over the years as an independent insurance agent.  Mental health services are often covered similar to PCP copays and allowances.  I hope people seek out the treatment needed.  Many illnesses can be linked to mental health issues/stress/worry.  Often talking to a therapist can provide much needed release of stress and guidance to point you in the direction if further care is needed.  The wholistic approach to healthcare has been embraced by many providers/insurance carriers.   Annual wellness/preventive care is crucial.  Take care of your mind and body! It is easier for some than others, but help is out there.

As a Big Sister through Big Brothers Big Sisters, Maui, I see all the time how zip code affects our overall health. A current misconception is children with overweight/obesity. I've been told the food provided by the school for children whose household meets the criteria for free meals is gross so my Little says she just doesn't eat. She's pretty much on her own in the food department. She does make good choices when given healthy options but what is she supposed to do when not given the option?

The point is, yes too much junk food causes overweight/obesity but having irregular meals & nutrient deficiencies causes large fluctuations in blood sugar leading to inflammation & fatigue which is more likely the cause of the overweight/obesity we are seeing in children.

What are your thoughts on this?

It makes me so happy that we are delving into this topic. As a nurse, as someone passionate about health, and as someone who grew up in poverty, I experienced first hand just how socioeconomic status widened the gap between my family and health and then witnessed it as a nurse in the field. The effects are devastating and span across generations. Nutrition is a crucial piece of health and even now, the portion of my income that is spent on organic, whole food for my family is astronomical and the time it takes to prepare that food is not something always available to those that are working long hours to make ends meet. It is imperative that as health technology advances, we ensure equal access to this technology. It is imperative that we incentivize health and bridge those gaps. Thanks for sharing, Martha.

Kuparuk Field was thought to have ultimate recoverable reserves of 1.6 billion barrels but has produced more than 2.5 billion barrels so far thanks to the efforts of exploration and development teams at ARCO/Phillips/ConocoPhillips and co-owners. The field had just begun production from 100% ARCO-owned acreage in December 1981 when I started work with ARCO in Anchorage. Discovery of the field marked a sad end for Sinclair ‚Äì they were a leader in North Slope exploration, but their management gave up prior to the Prudhoe Bay lease sale and they were acquired by Atlantic Richfield while Sinclair was drilling the well that discovered Kuparuk Field. One Sinclair manager offered to ‚Äúdrink all the oil that would ever be found on the North Slope.‚Äù Sinclair‚Äôs last well turned out to be the largest discovery in their history. (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/284188613_Kuparuk_River_Field_-_U_S_A_North_Slope_Alaska).

I‚Äôve never been blinded to the fact that there are differences that exist between myself (white) and people of color.  But one day, on my first day of work, at a hospital in Florida I was talking to a woman my age, who would become my closest friend.  Casual conversation, when meeting someone in Florida is: ‚Äúwhere are you from‚Äù?  Most people are transplants from other states, so to hear someone say they are from right here can be shocking lol.  So, I said oh wow‚Ä¶ so you were born right here in this hospital (knowing it was the only hospital in the county at that time.  Then she said those life changing words.. she said with a giggle, oh no girl, black people weren‚Äôt allowed to have babies in the hospital when I was born, I was born with a midwife at home.  I will never forget that statement nor the deep feelings it instilled into my soul.  I still want to grab her and hug her to this day.  So, that‚Äôs why I chose Anthem to be my employer.  Because Anthem knows everyone deserves equal access to healthcare and the benefits that good healthcare brings to all when we remove barriers to the social determinites of health!

Part of the problem is that Big Data cannot tell us causation, only correlation.  It can't tell us how things work, only which properties group together.  It's important for data scientists to retain the humility and recognize the limitations of the tools we have today.  

There's a school of thought that considers us all nexus of influences without free will.  It's a philosophical assumption, not a scientific fact.  Posts like these always assume this philosophy is accurate, using terms like "determinants" as if we're all predestined, fated for certain outcomes before we're born.  Posts like this never actually argue that we are indeed all dominos falling as fate has decided, they just assume it's true.

You can say that a lack of specialists in rural counties makes it less likely for people to receive certain care and negatively impacts outcomes.  But those people can move, and it's not clear that it's morally right to make the rest of society bear the costs of their decision making.  

I think our society needs to have an open conversation about whether humans actually have free will or if we're automatons, and what that means for policymaking and healthcare.

Yes, employee belonging is closely related to team cohesion.  I think the following three aspects can improve employees' sense of belonging. 
 1. Treat the employee as a "person" with feelings, thoughts and independent personality, not just the fulfillment of his job responsibilities.  Of course, when it comes to work, the strict requirements are to be strict, but the care after work cannot be less.  This can not only improve work efficiency, but also prevent employees from feeling disgusted, and have a sense of being cared for.

 2. Willingness to listen to employees.  Many times employees may have some small complaints or negative emotions. As a qualified leader, you should not only know how to curb, but should actively listen to the voices of employees. In fact, many times, the thing they complain about may be you.  A slight change can not only make employees more convincing, but also increase their sense of belonging.

 3. Value the opinions and ideas of employees.  As a leader, your ability may be higher than that of employees, but no one is perfect and omnipotent, and each employee will have his own strengths. Therefore, listening to the opinions and ideas of employees will sometimes yield different surprises.

In particular, the wide variety of materials used in common oilfield service, especially offshore or in harsh/toxic environments - this demands an inventory of various materials that erodes the space-saving benefits. Also, the availability of the digital assets on all of the necessary pieces/parts is essential - low cost providers (ie "mom & pops") will struggle with this. And, the certification of the newly made parts to relevant standards. All of these are addressable, in time.

I agree that employees are looking for Company's whose values align with themselves. As a Union employee at CUNA Mutual Group, I'm frustrated by our Company's proposals to cut our health insurance and freeze the pension plan. We provide quality insurance and pension plan products to thousands of people around the country - and its a shame that our own Company would propose cutting those things for their own workforce. That doesn't seem to align well with our corporate values at all.

Part of my personal values are that people and companies should practice what they preach.

A company stating that they stand for equity while making record-breaking profits but simultaneously cutting health care and refusing to increase salaries anywhere near current inflation rates, doesn't sound very equitable to me.

A company that "Helps People Protect, Invest and Plan for Their Future" while eliminating pensions for newly hired employees with nothing to take it's place doesn't sound like it's even helping it's own employees plan for their future, let alone anyone else.

#StrongerTogether is more than just a slogan, it has real meaning to both your customers and your employees. It takes all of us working together to be strong.

As an employee at CUNA Mutual Group, I find it a disturbing how big of a disconnect there is between the values we share publicly, and how we live them internally. I'm not sure how we can claim to be #StrongerTogether when the company is consistently outsourcing our jobs, currently attempting to strip our best healthcare options, and offering wage adjustments that potentially harm the financial futures of its employees.
He obviously was not involved in the hiring process.

I took a leap of faith to come to CUNA in 2020.  Through the entire pandemic, CUNA has consistently done the right things for employees.  Whether that be supporting health (including mental health), being flexible and understanding for time away from work, and allowing remote and hybrid work flexibility.  That was all great.  We all felt included, we all felt like we were in this together.  Ironic now though, that this post includes the hashtag #strongertogether  and speaks to corporate and personal values.  CUNA corporate values have remained stellar.  We just wish recollection of those corporate and personal values could manage to work their way into contract negotiations and for the bargaining teams to be on the same page, because they clearly do not appear to be.  If you want to be #strongertogether, good then we all do, so let's get it done.  Simple as that.

Agree that company's are working to create Diversity, Equity and Inclusion these days. Unfortunately CUNA Mutual Group wants to cut our union health insurance and freeze our pension plans, two very important products they sell to consumers around the world. Aren't we as union employees also consumers, working daily and trying to earn a decent wage to make a living? This falls short of equity and inclusion in my definition. Making record profits and proposing to cut many benefits for union employees doesn't align to our corporate values as I understand them.

1. Job security for ourselves and our community

4. Fair compensation that keeps up with inflation

Fewer than 1,000 bison remained after their extirpation with federal troops being sent into Yellowstone to protect the last remaining bison.  Many of the bison today are cattle hybrids as a result of extreme efforts to preserve the species.  Many populations are absent from their former ranges as a result of western expansion - elk, wolves, and bears.  ‚ÄúProgress‚Äù must not come at any cost lest we come to view its authors with more contempt than admiration.

This is the story I heard when I started at Nordstrom in Anchorage in 1988 from our store manager.  
Our customer service department received a quilt that was purchased from the store that had occupied our space YEARS prior, from a person (who had not been our customer) who was living in a bush community.  For those of you not from Alaska, the bush is a rural community.  The person requested we sew all the seams back together again, as it had started to age and come apart.  And we did it, cleaned it for them and sent it back out to them! No charge!  Why? Because we were NORDSTROM!  (and not Nordstroms, BTW) 

Customers first!  ‚ù§Ô∏è

(Also, Anchorage would like our store back!)

I‚Äôm curious‚Ä¶.did productivity suffer when everyone was sent home to work in 2020? I‚Äôve worked both in an office and at home for many years. I preferred a home base vs. office because I was more focused and I enjoyed the lack of drama and distraction often seen in an office environment. I‚Äôll take the high road here and say that most workers are grown ups and will know when there is a need to meet with their clients, coworkers, team, etc. in person, ideally in a lovely, well thought out environment. In the meantime, if modern technology allows people to work effectively from their home offices, what advantage is there in ‚Äúbringing people back into the office‚Äù? (I‚Äôve discussed this with several people from worker bees to SVP‚Äôs and exactly no one has told me that they can‚Äôt wait to get back to the office full time and that they‚Äôre looking forward to the commute.) Of course, 
everyone‚Äôs situation is different ( If I‚Äôd had a noisy household with kids running around I would have loved  to escape to a beautiful office to work, for example). I believe that the pandemic has taught us that ‚Äúless can be more‚Äù.

It has been an actual problem for decades. A lot of resistance comes from sites. There are fixed set up costs, and I have used competitive or dynamic enrollment models where you reallocate patients from underperforming sites to higher performing ones, but you need to have the infrastructure in the higher performing sites to handle the additional load, and the contracts you have with the underperforming institutional sites often do not allow reductions in costs. So, the annualized operating cost of performing the trial goes up. When I was in large Pharma the accountants hated that! 

It is not a problem, as it can be solved by money!

No site shares their enrollment data, and no company does.

What is almost needed is a NFP collecting site and disease specific enrollment data, which means anonymized protocol inclusion and exclusion data, overheads, etc. much like Tufts University Center for the Study of Drug Development did, and that can take a company protocol and run it through a model and identify the best sites, etc.

We all talk about "big data", but this is something that could meaningfully change the performance of clinical trials.

1) The heat spreader of the 7000 series adds 20C to the TDP = CPU run's hotter, if you remove that and put the heat sink + thermal past directly on the CPU chips, the CPU will run 20C cooler.

AMD need to sell 7000 series with and without the heat spreader so users have a choice.

2) Some of the AM4 socket CPU coolers (the type which bolt down using the 4 CPU cooler mount holes around the AM5 CPU socket) don't fit on the 7000 CPUs.

AMD need to fix this flaw with a bracket/adaptor.

AM4 socket CPU coolers which fit the 7000 series CPUs are the ones which clip on to the standard AMD CPU cooler mounts.

3) When applying thermal paste to the new design of heat spreader on the 7000 series, you can easily get thermal paste on to the rest of the CPU.

AMD need to make a plastic plate/guard which is placed on the CPU to stop this while spreading thermal paste. Once the paste has been spread you remove the plastic plate and attach the heat sink.

A couple of weeks ago I visited Pima air museum in Tucson and met a 99-year old B-17 radio operator who was a crew member of the aircraft named the HELNO-GAL. 

His name is Walter Ram and was shot down in June ‚Äò43 and became a POW at Stalag-17.  He was giving a talk to a number of people about his experiences including the freezing conditions aboard the B-17s and the brutal treatment the prisoners endured, concluding in a forced 300-mile march near the end of the war. 

I bought the book he just published (named HELNO-GAL) about his experiences from signing up to his post-war years and the realisation he suffered from PTSD, a condition not recognised at that time. 

It was a privilege to meet him, one of the last surviving members of the greatest generation and a true war hero.
